== Notes ==
{{IndicText}}
{{wikisourceauthor|Rabindranath Tagore}}
{{wikiquote|Rabindranath Tagore}}
<div class="references-small">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B1>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Indian English|<U+03B1>|none}} Narrow (Indian English) [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] transcription: {{IPA|[<U+0279>obin<U+032A>d<U+032A><U+027E>onat<U+032A><U+02B0> <U+0288><U+02B0>aku<U+0279>]}}.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B2>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Romanization|<U+03B2>|none}} [[Romanization|Romanized]] transliteration from Tagore's name in [[Bengali script#Bengali symbols|Bangla script]]: ''{{Unicode|Robindronath <U+0162>hakur}}''.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B3>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Birthdate|<U+03B3>|none}} In the [[Bangla Calendar]]: 25 [[Baishakh]], 1268 &ndash; 22 [[Srabon]], 1348.

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B4>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Gurudev|<U+03B4>|none}} "Gurudev" translates as "divine mentor".<ref name="Sil_2005">{{Harvnb|Sil|2005}}.</ref>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B5>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Jorasanko|<U+03B5>|none}} Tagore was born at No. 6 Dwarkanath Tagore Lane, Jorasanko &mdash; the address of the main mansion (the ''Jorasanko Thakurbari'') inhabited by the Jorasanko branch of the Tagore clan, which had earlier suffered an acrimonious split. Jorasanko was located in the Bengali section of Calcutta ({{Lang-bn|<U+0995><U+09B2><U+0995><U+09BE><U+09A4><U+09BE>}}), near Chitpur Road.<ref name="Dutta_1995_34">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=34}}.</ref>

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B6>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Visva-Bharati|<U+03B6>|none}} [[Etymology]] of "Visva-Bharati": from the [[Sanskrit]] term for "world" or "universe" and the name of a ''[[Rigveda]]'' goddess ("Bharati") associated with [[Saraswati]], the Hindu patron goddess of learning.<ref name="Dutta_1995_220">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=220}}.</ref> "Visva-Bharati" also translates as "India in the World".

&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''<U+03B7>.'''&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{Note_label|Controversy|<U+03B7>|none}} Tagore was mired in several notable controversies, including his dealings with Indian nationalists [[Subhas Chandra Bose]]<ref name="Sen_1997">{{Harvnb|Sen|1997}}.</ref> and [[Rash Behari Bose]],<ref name="Dutta_1995_214">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=214}}.</ref> his expressions of admiration for [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-style [[Communism]],<ref name="Dutta_1995_297">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=297}}.</ref><ref name="Dutta_1995_214-215">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|pp=214-215}}.</ref> and papers confiscated from Indian nationalists in New York allegedly implicating Tagore in a plot to use German funds to overthrow the British Raj.<ref name="Dutta_1995_212">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=212}}.</ref> The latter allegation caused Tagore's book sales and popularity among the U.S. public to plummet.<ref name="Dutta_1995_214">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=214}}.</ref> Lastly, his relations with and ambivalent opinion of Italian dictator [[Benito Mussolini]] revolted many, causing [[Romain Rolland]] (a close friend of Tagore's) to state that "[h]e is abdicating his role as moral guide of the independent spirits of Europe and India".<ref name="Dutta_1995_273">{{Harvnb|Dutta|Robinson|1995|p=273}}.</ref>
</div>

